[25.400361, "o", "curl(1)                                       curl Manual                                       curl(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       curl - transfer a URL\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcurl\u001b[0m \u001b[1m[options\u001b[0m \u001b[1m/\u001b[0m \u001b[1mURLs]\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mcurl\u001b[0m  is  a  tool  for transferring data from or to a server. It supports these protocols: DICT,\u001b[m\r\n       FILE, FTP, FTPS, GOPHER, GOPHERS, HTTP, HTTPS, IMAP, IMAPS,  LDAP,  LDAPS,  MQTT,  POP3,  POP3S,\u001b[m\r\n       RTMP,  RTMPS,  RTSP, SCP, SFTP, SMB, SMBS, SMTP, SMTPS, TELNET, TFTP, WS and WSS. The command is\u001b[m\r\n       designed to work without user interaction.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       curl offers a busload of useful tricks like proxy support, user authentication, FTP upload, HTTP\u001b[m\r\n       post, SSL connections, cookies, file transfer resume and more. As you will see below, the number\u001b[m\r\n       of features will make your head spin.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       curl is powered by libcurl for all transfer-related features. See \u001b[4mlib"]
[25.400399, "o", "curl(3)\u001b[24m for details.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mURL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The URL syntax is protocol-dependent. You find a detailed description in RFC 3986.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page curl(1) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
