[27.303472, "o", "\u001b[1;1Hcurl(1)                                       curl Manual                                       curl(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H       curl - transfer a URL\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H       \u001b[1mcurl\u001b[0m \u001b[1m[options\u001b[0m \u001b[1m/\u001b[0m \u001b[1mURLs]\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H       \u001b[1mcurl\u001b[0m  is  a  tool  for transferring data from or to a server. It supports these protocols: DICT,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H       FILE, FTP, FTPS, GOPHER, GOPHERS, HTTP, HTTPS, IMAP, IMAPS,  LDAP,  LDAPS,  MQTT,  POP3,  POP3S,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H       RTMP,  RTMPS,  RTSP, SCP, SFTP, SMB, SMBS, SMTP, SMTPS, TELNET, TFTP, WS and WSS. The command is\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H       designed to work without user interaction.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H       curl offers a busload of useful tricks like proxy support, user authentication, FTP upload, HTTP\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H       post, SSL connections, cookies, file transfer resume and more. As you will see below, the number\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H       of features will "]
[27.303576, "o", "make your head spin.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H       curl is powered by libcurl for all transfer-related features. See \u001b[4mlibcurl(3)\u001b[24m for details.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[21;1H\u001b[1mURL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[22;1H       The URL syntax is protocol-dependent. You find a detailed description in RFC 3986.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[23;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[24;1H\u001b[1;1Hcurl(1)                                       curl Manual                                       curl(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H       curl - transfer a URL\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H       \u001b[1mcurl\u001b[0m \u001b[1m[options\u001b[0m \u001b[1m/\u001b[0m \u001b[1mURLs]\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H       \u001b[1mcurl\u001b[0m  is  a  tool  for transferring data from or to a server. It supports these protocols: DICT,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H       FILE, FTP, FTPS, GOPHER, GOPHERS, HTTP, HTTPS, IMAP, IMAPS,  LDAP,  LDAPS,  MQTT,  POP3,  POP3S,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H       RTMP,  RTMPS,  RTSP, SCP, SFTP, SMB, SMBS, SMTP, SMTPS, TELNET, TFTP, WS and WSS. The command is\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H       designed to"]
[27.303589, "o", " work without user interaction.\u001b["]
[27.303807, "o", "m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H       curl offers a busload of useful tricks like proxy support, user authentication, FTP upload, HTTP\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H       post, SSL connections, cookies, file transfer resume and more. As you will see below, the number\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H       of features will make your head spin.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H       curl is powered by libcurl for all transfer-related features. See \u001b[4mlibcurl(3)\u001b[24m for details.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[21;1H\u001b[1mURL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[22;1H       The URL syntax is protocol-dependent. You find a detailed description in RFC 3986.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[23;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[24;1H"]
[27.30411, "o", "...skipping...\r\n              the  response-\u001b[7mheader\u001b[27ms,  thus  possibly inducing an extra network round-trip. This is used\u001b[m\r\n              instead of setting a specific authentication method, which you can do with \u001b[4m--basic\u001b[24m, \u001b[4m--di‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mgest\u001b[24m, \u001b[4m--ntlm\u001b[24m, and \u001b[4m--negotiate\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Using  \u001b[4m--anyauth\u001b[24m  is  not  recommended if you do uploads from stdin, since it may require\u001b[m\r\n              data to be sent twice and then the client must be able to  rewind.  If  the  need  should\u001b[m\r\n              arise when uploading from stdin, the upload operation will fail.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Used together with \u001b[4m-u,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--user\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Providing \u001b[4m--anyauth\u001b[24m multiple times has no extra effect.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Example:\u001b[m\r\n               curl --anyauth --user me:pwd https://example.com\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              See also \u001b[4m--proxy-anyauth\u001b[24m, \u001b[4m--basic\u001b[24m and \u001b[4m--digest\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       -a, "]
[27.304127, "o", "--append\u001b[m\r\n              (FTP  SFTP)  When used in an upload, this makes curl append to the target file instead of\u001b[m\r\n              overwriting it. If the remote file does not exist, it will be  created.  Note  that  this\u001b[m\r\n              flag is ignored by some SFTP servers (including OpenSSH).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Providing  \u001b[4m-a,\u001b[24m  \u001b[4m--append\u001b[24m multiple times has no extra effect.  Disable it again with --no-\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page curl(1) line 201 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[29.193788, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[29.193961, "o", "...skipping...\r\n              authentication \u001b[7mheader\u001b[27ms.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              The  region  argument is a string that points to a geographic area of a resources collec‐\u001b[m\r\n              tion (region-code) when the region name is omitted from the endpoint.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              The service argument is a string that points to a function provided by a cloud  (service-\u001b[m\r\n              code) when the service name is omitted from the endpoint.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              If \u001b[4m--aws-sigv4\u001b[24m is provided several times, the last set value will be used.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Example:\u001b[m\r\n               curl --aws-sigv4 \"aws:amz:east-2:es\" --user \"key:secret\" https://example.com\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              See also \u001b[4m--basic\u001b[24m and \u001b[4m-u,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--user\u001b[24m. Added in 7.75.0.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       --basic\u001b[m\r\n              (HTTP)  Tells curl to use HTTP Basic authentication with the remote host. This is the de‐\u001b[m\r\n              fault and this option is usually pointless, unless you use it to  override  a  pre"]
[29.193975, "o", "viously\u001b[m\r\n              set  option  that  sets  a  different authentication method (such as \u001b[4m--ntlm\u001b[24m, \u001b[4m--digest\u001b[24m, or\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4m--negotiate\u001b[24m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Used together with \u001b[4m-u,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--user\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page curl(1) line 235 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[30.370306, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[30.371195, "o", "...skipping...\r\n              matically decompress the content. \u001b[7mHeader\u001b[27ms are not modified.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              If  this option is used and the server sends an unsupported encoding, curl will report an\u001b[m\r\n              error. This is a request, not an order; the server may  or  may  not  deliver  data  com‐\u001b[m\r\n              pressed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Providing  \u001b[4m--compressed\u001b[24m  multiple times has no extra effect.  Disable it again with --no-\u001b[m\r\n              compressed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Example:\u001b[m\r\n               curl --compressed https://example.com\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              See also \u001b[4m--compressed-ssh\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       -K, --config <file>\u001b[m\r\n              Specify a text file to read curl arguments from. The command line arguments found in  the\u001b[m\r\n              text file will be used as if they were provided on the command line.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Options and their parameters must be specified on the same line in the file, separated by\u001b[m\r\n              whitespace, c"]
[30.371206, "o", "olon, or the equals sign. Long option names can optionally be given  in  the\u001b[m\r\n              config  file  without the initial double dashes and if so, the colon or equals characters\u001b[m\r\n              can be used as separators. If the option is specified with one or two dashes,  there  can\u001b[m\r\n              be no colon or equals character between the option and its parameter.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page curl(1) line 423 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[30.828649, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[30.829241, "o", "...skipping...\r\n              See also \u001b[4m--resolve\u001b[24m and \u001b[4m-H,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--\u001b[24m\u001b[4m\u001b[7mheader\u001b[27m\u001b[24m. Added in 7.49.0.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       -C, --continue-at <offset>\u001b[m\r\n              Continue/Resume a previous file transfer at the given offset. The given offset is the ex‐\u001b[m\r\n              act  number of bytes that will be skipped, counting from the beginning of the source file\u001b[m\r\n              before it is transferred to the destination. If used with uploads, the FTP server command\u001b[m\r\n              SIZE will not be used by curl.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Use  \"-C  -\"  to tell curl to automatically find out where/how to resume the transfer. It\u001b[m\r\n              then uses the given output/input files to figure that out.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              If \u001b[4m-C,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--continue-at\u001b[24m is provided several times, the last set value will be used.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Examples:\u001b[m\r\n               curl -C - https://example.com\u001b[m\r\n               curl -C 400 https://example.com\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              See also "]
[30.829252, "o", "\u001b[4m-r,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--range\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       -c, --cookie-jar <filename>\u001b[m\r\n              (HTTP) Specify to which file you want curl to write all cookies after a completed  opera‐\u001b[m\r\n              tion.  Curl writes all cookies from its in-memory cookie storage to the given file at the\u001b[m\r\n              end of operations. If no cookies are known, no data will be written.  The  file  will  be\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page curl(1) line 545 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[31.224164, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[31.224337, "o", "...skipping...\r\n              (HTTP)  Pass  the data to the HTTP server in the Cookie \u001b[7mheader\u001b[27m. It is supposedly the data\u001b[m\r\n              previously received from the server in a \"Set-Cookie:\" line. The data should  be  in  the\u001b[m\r\n              format \"NAME1=VALUE1; NAME2=VALUE2\". This makes curl use the cookie \u001b[7mheader\u001b[27m with this con‐\u001b[m\r\n              tent explicitly in all outgoing request(s). If multiple requests are done due to  authen‐\u001b[m\r\n              tication, followed redirects or similar, they will all get this cookie passed on.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              If  no  '='  symbol  is used in the argument, it is instead treated as a filename to read\u001b[m\r\n              previously stored cookie from. This option also activates the cookie  engine  which  will\u001b[m\r\n              make  curl  record incoming cookies, which may be handy if you are using this in combina‐\u001b[m\r\n              tion with the \u001b[4m-L,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--location\u001b[24m option or do multiple URL transfers on the same  invoke.  If\u001b["]
[31.224374, "o", "m\r\n       "]
[31.224415, "o", "       the file name is exactly a minus (\"-\"), curl will instead read the contents from stdin.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              The file format of the file to read cookies from should be plain HTTP \u001b[7mheader\u001b[27ms (Set-Cookie\u001b[m\r\n              style) or the Netscape/Mozilla cookie file format.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              The file specified with \u001b[4m-b,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--cookie\u001b[24m is only used as input. No cookies will be written to\u001b[m\r\n              the file. To store cookies, use the \u001b[4m-c,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--cookie-jar\u001b[24m option.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              If  you use the Set-Cookie file format and do not specify a domain then the cookie is not\u001b[m\r\n              sent since the domain will never match. To address this, set a domain in Set-Cookie  line\u001b[m\r\n              (doing that will include sub-domains) or preferably: use the Netscape format.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Users  often  want  to  both read cookies from a file and write updated cookies back to a\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page curl(1) line 587 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[31.751157, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[31.751359, "o", "              file, so using both \u001b[4m-b,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--cookie\u001b[24m and \u001b[4m-c,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--cookie-jar\u001b[24m in the same command line is common.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page curl(1) line 589 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[32.28364, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[32.283784, "o", "              \u001b[4m-b,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--cookie\u001b[24m can be used several times in a command line\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Examples:\u001b[m\r\n               curl -b cookiefile https://example.com\u001b[m\r\n               curl -b cookiefile -c cookiefile https://example.com\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              See also \u001b[4m-c,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--cookie-jar\u001b[24m and \u001b[4m-j,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--junk-session-cookies\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       --create-dirs\u001b[m\r\n              When used in conjunction with the \u001b[4m-o,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--output\u001b[24m option, curl will create the necessary lo‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page curl(1) line 599 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[32.688098, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[32.689255, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       -D, --dump-\u001b[7mheader\u001b[27m <filename>\u001b[m\r\n              (HTTP FTP) Write the received protocol \u001b[7mheader\u001b[27ms to the specified file. If no  \u001b[7mheader\u001b[27ms  are\u001b[m\r\n              received, the use of this option will create an empty file.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              When  used  in FTP, the FTP server response lines are considered being \"\u001b[7mheader\u001b[27ms\" and thus\u001b[m\r\n              are saved there.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Having multiple transfers in one set of operations (i.e.  the  URLs  in  one  \u001b[4m-:,\u001b[24m  \u001b[4m--next\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              clause), will append them to the same file, separated by a blank line.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              If \u001b[4m-D,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--dump-\u001b[24m\u001b[4m\u001b[7mheader\u001b[27m\u001b[24m is provided several times, the last set value will be used.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Example:\u001b[m\r\n               curl --dump-\u001b[7mheader\u001b[27m store.txt https://example.com\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              See also \u001b[4m-o,\u001b[24m \u001b[4m--output\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       --egd-file <file>\u001b[m\r\n              (TLS)  Deprecated"]
[32.689267, "o", "  option.  This option is ignored by curl since 7.84.0. Prior to that it\u001b[m\r\n              only had an effect on curl if built to use old versions of OpenSSL.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n              Specify the path name to the Entropy Gathering Daemon socket. The socket is used to  seed\u001b[m\r\n              the random engine for SSL connections.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page curl(1) line 996 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
